# Android Deployment Plan (Ascend Workout Tracker)

**Goal:** Ship an Android version via Google Play with feature parity to iOS, using the existing React/Vite + Capacitor architecture, Supabase backend, and RevenueCat for IAP.

---

## 0) Assumptions and Non-Goals

### Assumptions
- Web app is already stable and shipped (or close) via Vercel.
- Native wrapper uses Capacitor and already exists for iOS.
- Auth is Supabase; purchases are RevenueCat via `@revenuecat/purchases-capacitor`.
- Dev environment is macOS.

### Non-goals (for first Android release)
- Perfect tablet UX
- Deep-link-based password reset fully inside native (can be web-based initially)
- Complex background sync
- Push notifications (unless you explicitly want reminders in v1 Android)

---

## 1) Prereqs: Accounts, Tools, and Local Environment

### Required accounts
- [ ] Google Play Console developer account (needed to publish)
- [ ] RevenueCat project access for Android setup

### Required tools on Mac
- [ ] Android Studio (SDK + emulator + platform tools)
- [ ] JDK 17 (Temurin/Adoptium recommended)
- [ ] Node.js LTS (already in use)
- [ ] Optional but recommended: `fastlane` for repeatable Play releases
- [ ] Optional but recommended: Sentry or Firebase Crashlytics (crash reporting)

### Local sanity checks
- [ ] `node -v` matches your repo expectations (LTS)
- [ ] `java -version` reports 17.x
- [ ] Android Studio installs:
  - [ ] Android SDK Platform (target SDK)
  - [ ] Build Tools
  - [ ] Platform Tools (adb)
  - [ ] Emulator + at least one device image

---

## 2) Add Android Platform to Capacitor

### Install the Android platform dependency
- [ ] `npm i @capacitor/android`

### Add Android project
- [ ] `npx cap add android`

### Add convenience scripts (package.json)
Add scripts similar to your existing iOS ones:
- [ ] `"cap:sync:android": "npm run build && npx cap sync android"`
- [ ] `"cap:open:android": "npx cap open android"`

### First build + open in Android Studio
- [ ] `npm run cap:sync:android`
- [ ] `npm run cap:open:android`

**Milestone:** App launches in Android emulator and on a physical device.

---

## 3) Environment and Config: Things to Decide Early

### App identity
- [ ] Decide Android package name (applicationId), e.g. `com.yourcompany.ascend`
- [ ] Decide Play Store app name (display name can differ from package)
- [ ] Verify Capacitor appId matches intended package

### Signing strategy
- [ ] Use Play App Signing (recommended)
- [ ] Keep keystore secure (even if Play manages final signing)

### Versioning strategy
Android requires:
- **versionName** (human-readable, e.g. `1.2.0`)
- **versionCode** (integer, must increase every release)
- [ ] Adopt a policy (e.g. versionCode = build number)

---

## 4) Highest-Risk Functional Areas to Validate on Android

These tend to behave differently in WebView vs desktop Safari/Chrome:

### Auth & password reset (important)
- [ ] Confirm password reset links work for Android users.
- [ ] **Recommendation:** Use a real HTTPS `redirectTo` for reset (e.g. a Vercel-hosted reset page),
      not `window.location.origin`, because native origins are not public URLs.
- [ ] Confirm the reset flow is tested end-to-end from an Android email client.

### Storage & offline behavior (Dexie/IndexedDB)
- [ ] Validate local data persistence across:
  - [ ] app close/reopen
  - [ ] device restart
  - [ ] OS “clear recent apps”
- [ ] Validate schema migrations if you use Dexie versioning
- [ ] Validate large-ish dataset behavior (weeks of workouts)

### Network transitions + resume behavior
- [ ] Put phone in airplane mode mid-session; ensure no corrupt state
- [ ] Background the app and resume; ensure state rehydrates cleanly

### IAP gating (RevenueCat)
- [ ] Confirm `Capacitor.isNativePlatform()` gates correctly on Android
- [ ] Confirm purchase and restore flows work on Android test accounts

**Milestone:** “Core user loop works on Android”: sign in, view workouts, log workout, sync, purchase, premium unlock.

