## 6) Build, Release, and QA Workflow

### Build types
- Debug: local dev, faster iteration
- Release: what you ship; must be signed and proguard/r8 may apply

### Suggested cadence
1. **Internal test build** (fast, minimal friction)
2. Fix critical Android-specific issues
3. Add crash reporting + basic analytics
4. “Closed testing” with a small group
5. Production release

### QA checklist (before moving beyond internal testing)
- [ ] Install and open app on:
  - [ ] Emulator (at least one)
  - [ ] Physical Android phone (at least one mid-range device if possible)
- [ ] Auth:
  - [ ] sign up
  - [ ] sign in
  - [ ] sign out
  - [ ] password reset
- [ ] Core functionality:
  - [ ] create/edit/delete workout entries
  - [ ] data persists across relaunch
  - [ ] sync works
- [ ] Purchases:
  - [ ] purchase
  - [ ] restore
  - [ ] entitlement persists after reinstall (if expected)
- [ ] Connectivity edge cases:
  - [ ] offline state
  - [ ] regain connectivity
- [ ] UI:
  - [ ] keyboard interactions
  - [ ] safe areas / status bar overlays
  - [ ] dark mode (if supported)

---

## 7) Operational Hardening (Recommended Before Production)

### Crash + error monitoring (high leverage)
Pick one:
- [ ] Sentry (cross-platform)
- [ ] Firebase Crashlytics (Android-native strength)

Minimum:
- [ ] capture unhandled JS errors
- [ ] capture native crashes
- [ ] attach app version + platform + device model

### Release automation (optional but saves time)
- [ ] GitHub Actions workflow that:
  - [ ] installs deps
  - [ ] builds web bundle
  - [ ] runs `npx cap sync android`
  - [ ] builds AAB in Gradle
  - [ ] outputs artifact

Later:
- [ ] fastlane supply to upload to Play tracks

### Secrets and config hygiene
- [ ] Ensure Supabase keys and endpoints are managed via environment variables properly for Android builds
- [ ] Avoid shipping secrets inside the binary (public anon keys are ok; service keys are not)
- [ ] Confirm any redirect URLs / deep link domains are explicitly configured

